ce:section.ce:para:
The EEM maps of the fabricated CQDs at three different pH values are shown in Fig. 2
                     . The obtained CQD suspensions were diluted twice with pure water for the measurements. The vertical and lateral axes of the map denoted emission and excitation wavelengths, respectively. It is worth noting that the maximum values of the color bars for charcoal and plain were 1.00 and 0.24, respectively. Because charcoal and plain CQDs were synthesized with 25 g and 1 g materials, respectively, the comparison of intensity is meaningless. Concentrating on Ex and Em wavelengths at pH 7.0, the CQDs from charcoal had 315 ± 0 nm and 436 ± 0 nm, respectively. At pH 7.0, the excitation and emission wavelengths of plain CQDs were 365 ± 0 nm and 436 ± 1 nm, respectively (see numerical values in Fig. 3
                     ). Although the Ex wavelengths of CQDs made from charcoal and plain coconut husks were similar, the Em wavelengths were significantly different. The FL intensities of CQDs derived from charcoal were greater at higher pH values, whereas those of CQDs derived from plain were decreased at higher pH values.
